---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';
import { breadcrumbSchema } from '../lib/schema';

const title = `Methodology, How we rate platforms | ${SITE.name}`;
const description = `Exactly how we evaluate legal sweepstakes casino alternatives: legal model, per-state availability, risk level, and verification. No hidden scores, no pay-to-rank.`;
const crumbs = [{ name: 'Home', path: '/' }, { name: 'Methodology', path: '/methodology' }];
---
<Base title={title} description={description} schema={[breadcrumbSchema(crumbs)]} canonical="/methodology">
  <Breadcrumbs crumbs={crumbs} />
  <article class="container-x py-10">
    <div class="prose-content mx-auto max-w-prose">
      <p class="mono-meta uppercase tracking-widest text-accent">Methodology</p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 font-head text-h1 text-ink">How we rate platforms</h1>
      <p class="mt-6">
        Our ratings are built on four things we can actually verify, not vibes, not a secret score,
        and not how much a platform pays us. Here's the whole system.
      </p>

      <h2>1. Legal model</h2>
      <p>
        We start by identifying exactly how a platform stays legal. Is it
        <a href="/guides/parimutuel-explained">parimutuel</a>,
        <a href="/guides/dfs-vs-casino">peer-to-peer DFS</a>,
        <a href="/guides/single-currency-model">single-currency</a>, a
        <a href="/guides/prediction-markets">prediction market</a>, or something else? A platform
        that can't or won't explain its legal basis is a red flag, and we treat it as one.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Per-state availability</h2>
      <p>
        Legality is state-specific. We verify whether each platform operates in each banned state
        rather than assuming that "available somewhere" means "available everywhere." A platform
        legal in California may not serve New York, and we mark that explicitly.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Risk level</h2>
      <p>
        We assign each platform a risk level, Low, Medium, High, or Unknown, based on how
        established and tested its legal model is. Decades-old models like parimutuel earn Low.
        Newer models earn Medium. Strained structures earn High. When we can't confirm the model at
        all, we say <strong>Unknown</strong> and decline to recommend it until we can.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Last verified</h2>
      <p>
        Every platform entry and review carries a "last verified" date. In a space where laws change
        monthly and platforms enter and exit states without notice, <em>when</em> we checked is as
        important as what we found. We aim to re-verify regularly and to reflect status changes
        within 48 hours of learning about them.
      </p>

      <h2>What we deliberately don't do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>We don't sell rankings. Affiliate relationships never change a platform's position or rating.</li>
        <li>We don't invent review scores. If we don't have a documented basis for a number, we don't publish one.</li>
        <li>We don't hide the negatives. Limitations, caps, and risks are stated plainly.</li>
        <li>We don't fabricate testimonials or self-awarded "best of" badges.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Sources</h2>
      <p>
        Where possible, we link factual legal claims to primary sources, legislation text,
        regulator statements, and operator announcements. If you spot something out of date,
        email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a> and we'll fix it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
